  "prompt": "This sentence has two verbs: \"will look\u201d and \"go.\u201d How do I understand this grammatical construct?",
  "response": "In the sentence, \"will look\" and \"go\" are indeed both verbs, but they serve different grammatical functions. Let's break it down:\n\n1. **\"Will look\"**:\n   - **\"Will\"** is an auxiliary verb (also known as a helping verb) used to form the future tense.\n   - **\"Look\"** is the main verb that indicates the action.\n\nWhen combined, \"will look\" forms the future tense of the verb \"look,\" meaning that the action of looking will happen in the future.\n\n2. **\"Go\"**:\n   - **\"Go\"** is another main verb and it indicates the action of moving from one place to another.\n\nIn a sentence, these verbs can be part of different clauses or can be sequential actions. For example:\n\n- **Sequential actions**: \"I will look for my keys and then go to the store.\"\n  - Here, \"will look\" and \"go\" are part of sequential actions, indicating what the speaker will do first and then what they will do next.\n\n- **Different clauses**: \"I will look at the map before you go.\"\n  - Here, \"will look\" is part of the main clause, and \"go\" is part of the dependent clause introduced by \"before.\"\n\nUnderstanding the grammatical construct involves identifying the roles of the verbs in the sentence and how they contribute to the overall meaning.",
